1. Creating data set of median home prices

Here is the code. 
#resources:
# median house price LA: https://www.zillow.com/home-values/12447/los-angeles-ca/
# median house price SD: https://www.zillow.com/home-values/54296/san-diego-ca/
# median house price Sac: https://www.zillow.com/home-values/20288/sacramento-ca/
# median house price SF: https://www.zillow.com/home-values/20330/san-francisco-ca/
house_prices_CA <- data.frame(metro_area = c(
                                         'Sacramento', 'Sacramento',
                                         'Sacramento', 'Sacramento',
                                         'LosAngeles', 'LosAngeles', 
                                         'LosAngeles', 'LosAngeles', 
                                         'SanDiego', 'SanDiego',
                                         'SanDiego', 'SanDiego',
                                         'SanFrancisco', 'SanFrancisco',
                                         'SanFrancisco', 'SanFrancisco'),
                              year = c('2015', '2016','2017','2018',
                                       '2015', '2016', '2017', '2018',
                                       '2015', '2016','2017','2018',
                                       '2015', '2016','2017','2018'),
                              avg_house_price = c(245447, 272402, 300190, 325171, #LA
                                                   562073, 605462, 647424, 700455, #SAC
                                                   497316, 529688, 567405, 611114, #SD
                                                   1109257, 1190377, 
                                                   1227453, 1358550 #SF
                                                   )) |>
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year))

2. Joining home prices dataset with avocados dataset

Here is the code. 
# resource: join by multiple columns
# https://www.statology.org/dplyr-join-on-multiple-columns/
avocados_CA <- avocados_metro |> 
  filter(metro_area %in% c('LosAngeles', 'Sacramento',
                            'SanDiego', 'SanFrancisco')) |>
  rename(avg_avocado_price = average_price)

CA_houses_avocados <- avocados_CA |>
  left_join(house_prices_CA, by = c("metro_area" = "metro_area", "year" = "year")) |>
  select(metro_area, year, total_volume, avg_avocado_price, avg_house_price) |>
  group_by(metro_area, year) |>
  summarise(avg_avocado_price_yearly = round(mean(avg_avocado_price), digits = 2),
            avg_avocado_volume_yearly = round(mean(total_volume), digits = 2),
            avg_house_price = mean(avg_house_price)
            )

3. Plotting annual avocado price vs.Â average house prices!

Here is the code. 
#scatter plot
CA_houses_avocados |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = avg_avocado_price_yearly,
                       y = (avg_house_price/100000))) +
  geom_point(aes(color = metro_area,
                 alpha = year)) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se = FALSE) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 13, by = 1)) +
  labs(x = "Average Avocado Price (USD)",
       y = "Average House Price (100,000 USD)",
       title = "Average House and Avocados Prices in CA, 2015-2018")

A joke in the media is that Millennials canât afford houses, because they spend all their money buying avocado toast. Letâs use this dataset to address that claim.

From the scatter plot of average annual avocado prices and average annual house prices (annual averages from 2015-2018) in California above, I donât believe that there is a relationship between house prices and avocado prices. As the average avocado price increases, the annual average house price doesnât necessarily increase as well. This is evident where average avocado prices in Sacramento were higher than those of Los Angelesâ avocado prices, yet Sacramentoâs house prices were lower than those of Los Angelesâ. In a visual sense, not all of the points are clustered around the linear regression line; if the points were all clustered or mostly clustered with a few outliers, then there could be a possibility of a relationship between the two average prices.

In the second plot of annual average house prices and average avocados sold, we can observe that the linear regression line is a poor fit for the averages in each of the 4 California reasons. Furthermore, since there is no clear linear relationship between the average number of avocados sold in a year and average house prices, no matter what California region weâre looking at.
